Good post, Ted, and I agree. It doesn&#039;t make sense to rant and rave about issues, when there are more productive ways to make your point.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I took this differently than Brent. Pointing out flaws, or noting decisions seem to not make sense, as Brent did in his post, isn&#039;t flaming the product, development team, or company. Calling them (devs, managers, etc) stupid for not changing something is. All too often I do see people ranting or flaming and making it personal when it isn&#039;t. It&#039;s a business decision, great one or poor one, that was made. You can seek to influence, and you can do so loudly, but you don&#039;t need to do so rudely.

